 beta-carotene, all of which apples contain. A well-known source of omega-3 fatty acids, consuming walnuts can improve lung function, reducing the risk of asthma and other respiratory conditions. These omega-3 fatty acids contain anti-inflammatory nutrients which protect against inflammatory ailments. Our list would definitely be incomplete without mentioning ginger. This well-known spice is not just anti-inflammatory; it is also a great detoxifier, removing toxins from the lungs while improvising circulation. Often used alongside ginger, garlic contains flavonoids that stimulate glutathione production, needed to remove toxins and carcinogens from the lungs, boosting lung health. Not meant for only its skin brightening properties, turmeric contains curcumin, a compound that relieves information of the airways and tightness of chests often experienced with asthma. An important addition to your smoothies, flaxseeds possess great benefits for your lungs. Berry lovers have nothing to lose when it comes to lung health. Especially acai and blueberries. Rich in vitamin C, which fights cell-damaging free radicals, berries are welcomed to a lung healthy diet. While adding all of this to your diet, it is also important to drink a lot of water. A proven detoxifier, water is important to ensure circulation and hydration in your lungs.  